Trish Zornio is TRIGGERED! She stole my photographs from the Elizabeth Warren event, then when confronted privately about it, said I was at the Elizabeth Warren event to "stalk" her. I'm big big confused. Here is the proof she stole the photography from the Warren event. Notice that she doesn't mention me by name, and she resorts to "gender" and saying that I am a "GOP Tracker". LMAO. https://www.joeycamp2020.com/2020/02/trish-zornio.html ~JojoRunning for office as a woman comes with unique challenges. Many weeks ago I was warned I was possibly being followed/stalked at events. A few weeks ago it began to escalate and even my opponent’s team warned me of this person in writing. At a political rally this past weekend I was targeted by this same person who wouldn’t leave me alone. Now we have incoming abusive threats every few minutes to hours from the same person because I will not respond to him or his threats. After two days and what must be hundreds of messages and fake content across multiple media platforms, today we got a glimpse of who we are dealing with. I share this not because I need help, but because I think it’s important for the public to get a glimpse of what really happens when women run for federal office. I never thought running for US Senate would be easy — I knew I’d get a GOP tracker (true), that my opponents would unfairly smear me in efforts to win (true), and that I’d put myself in a personally vulnerable position financially, emotionally, and otherwise (also true). I’m still so honored and excited to be running, and I’m working so hard to make the ballot (!), but for all the amazing things that happen and people I meet, there truly are many downright ugly experiences on the campaign trail — especially for women. Thankfully, these kind of experiences only serve to make me more passionate than ever to fight for change and especially to fight for women’s rights and safety. No man will ever keep me down! 😉  Have a great morning everyone, and in the spirit of asking for what we need, feel free to leave a little extra positive feedback to counteract. We women (and men!) have to stick together and lift each other when the going gets tough. Let’s do this — it’s caucus time!  #NeverthelessShePersisted

New Colorado State Legislative Session, update by Representative Leslie Herod. ~Joey *Plain Text* "Dear Friends and Neighbors, The 2020 Legislative Session is underway! Although there was much pomp and circumstance during week one, we have also been hard at work. In fact, over 90 bills have been introduced in the House and 70 in the Senate already. During opening day Speaker KC Becker spoke about the historic and productive 2019 session which saw a majority-women house of representatives leading the way on lowering the cost of health care, investing in education, tackling climate change and reforming our criminal legal system. Moving forward, the Speaker outlined an ambitious agenda for 2020 including ending capital punishment, increasing mental health support in our schools, implementing gun safety initiatives that have already been adopted on a bipartisan basis around the country, raising the legal age to buy nicotine and tobacco products to 21 and passing a fiscally sustainable paid family leave program. Governor Jared Polis gave a bold State of the State address that addressed many of the issues that I have been championing. These measures include reforming our broken bail system, making college more affordable and expanding mental health and substance use services to those who need it.  I look forward to working with Governor Polis and leaders in both chambers on our shared priorities, including:   - Making college attainable  - Investing in preschool and K-12 education  - Taking action on every front to address the opioid epidemic  - Lowering the cost of prescription drugs  - Reforming our bail and pretrial system  - Enacting Paid Family Leave for all Coloradans  - Increasing renewable energy As always, most of my legislative initiatives come from you, including upcoming legislation to ban discrimination on the basis of hairstyle and require insurance companies to cover treatment for infertility.  There are many more bills to come. Follow me on twitter and facebook for legislative updates and announcements of community events. Thank you for your support. Boldly Forward,"

In Colorado it is a crime to "Attempt to Influence" 2016 Colorado Revised Statutes Title 18 - Criminal Code Article 8 - Offenses - Governmental Operations Part 3 - Bribery and Corrupt Influences § 18-8-306. Attempt to influence a public servant "Any person who attempts to influence any public servant by means of deceit or by threat of violence or economic reprisal against any person or property, with the intent thereby to alter or affect the public servant's decision, vote, opinion, or action concerning any matter which is to be considered or performed by him or the agency or body of which he is a member, commits a class 4 felony." According to Wheat Ridge Police Department Defective Detective Mark Slavsky if you "Attempt to Influence" by means of threats of litigation you are guilty of this offense.
